Stats SA announced that retail sales were down 0.2% year-on-year in October following a revised increase of 1.6% in September. JOHANNESBURG - Retail sales unexpectedly fell for the first time this year in October, suggesting the South African Reserve Bank might continue to hold off raising interest rates in January to take pressure off the economy.The central bank has hiked the benchmark repo by a total of 200 basis points since early 2014, but has kept it unchanged at 7% since the last increase in March as economic growth, traditionally driven by consumer demand, remains weak.Earlier on Wednesday, Statistics South Africa announced that retail sales were down 0.2% year-on-year in October following a revised increase of 1.6% in September.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)